  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 17:3-4",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Chronicles 17:3-4",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He walked in the first ways of his father David — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "His ways before he fell so foully, in the matter of Uriah, which were good ways. David, indeed, recovered from that fall, but, perhaps, never, while he lived, fully retrieved the spiritual strength and comfort which he had lost. Jehoshaphat followed David as far as he followed God, and no farther. St. Paul himself thus limits our imitation of him, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 11:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Follow me, as I follow Christ, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and not otherwise. The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "first ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "ways of many pious people have been their best ways, and their ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "first love ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "their strongest love: which, however, ought not to be the case: for the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "last ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "ought to be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "more than the first, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 2:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But in every copy we propose to write after, as we ought to single out that only which is good, so that chiefly which is best. The original words here are literally rendered, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He walked in the ways of David his father, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "הראשׁונים",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "hareshonim, those first, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ancient ways. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He proposed to himself, for his example, the primitive times of the royal family, those purest times, before the corruptions of the late reigns came in. See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 6:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The LXX. leave out ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "David, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and so refer this to Asa: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He walked in the first ways of his father ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Asa, and did not imitate him in what was amiss in him toward the latter end of his time. It is well to be cautious in following the best men, lest we step aside after them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And sought not unto Baalim — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The neighbouring nations had their Baalim: one had one Baal, and another had another; but he abhorred them all, and had nothing to do with any of them. He ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sought the Lord God of his father, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and him only; prayed to him only; and inquired of him only.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "17:1-19 Jehoshaphat promotes religion in Judah, His prosperity. - Jehoshaphat found his people generally very ignorant, and therefore endeavoured to have them well taught. The public teaching of the word of God forms, in all ages, the great method of promoting the power of godliness. Thereby the understanding is informed, the conscience is awakened and directed. We have a particular account of Jehoshaphat's prosperity. But it was not his formidable army that restrained the neighbouring nations from attempting any thing against Israel, but the fear of God which fell upon them, when Jehoshaphat reformed his country, and set up a preaching ministry in it. The ordinances of God are more the strength and safety of a kingdom, than soldiers and weapons of war. The Bible requires use to notice the hand of God in every event, yet this is little regarded. But let all employ the talents they have: be faithful, even in that which is little. Set up the worship of God in your houses. The charge of a family is important. Why should you not instruct them as Jehoshaphat did his subjects, in the book of the law of the Lord. But be consistent. Do not recommend one thing, and practise another. Begin with yourselves. Seek to the Lord God of Israel, then call upon children and servants to follow your example.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The first ways of his father David - The Septuagint and several Hebrew manuscripts omit \"David,\" which has probably crept in from the margin, for David's \"first ways\" are nowhere else contrasted with his later ways. The real meaning of the writer is, that Jehoshaphat followed the example set by his father Asa in his earlier years ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 14:1-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; 15.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Baalim - On the plural form, see 1 Kings 18:18 note. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Baalim - On the plural form, see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Kings 18:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " note. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
